               <head>Hafiz-i Abru's geography, books 1-2</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Jughrāfiyā-yi Ḥāfiẓ Abrū by Ḥāfiẓ Abrū</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85053991 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85135483 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85067895" n="1" xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_3874-item1">
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="person_22865925">Ḥāfiẓ Abrū</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="per" key="person_22865925">حافظ ابرو</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="work_7920">Jughrāfiyā-yi Ḥāfiẓ Abrū</title>
                     <title xml:lang="per" key="work_7920">جغرافیای حافظ ابرو</title>
                     <note>
                        <p>Geographical history begun in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari">817 </date>under the orders of the Timurid ruler Mīrzā Shāh Rukh ibn Amīr Tīmūr bringing the history of Khurāsān down to <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari">821</date>, the latest event mentioned being the death of Amīrzādah Saʿd Vaqqās 
                        </p>
                        <p>Consists of books 1-2, but defective at end</p>
                        <p>Lacking colophon or date</p>
                        <p>Datable to late-sixteenth-century Shiraz, Safavid Iran</p>
                        <p>Seal partially obliterated (f. 1r), but probably is that of the Iranian minister, Muḥammad Shafīʿ</p>
                        <p>Transcribed by multiple hands in nastaʿlīq</p>
                        <p>Large illuminated double page openings (ff. 4v-5r, 7v-8r, 175v-176r), with bold sarlawḥ and ʿunvān designs on folios 4v, 7v, and 175v</p>
                        <p>Illuminated diagram of the known world organised schematically into climes or aqālīm (ff. 6v-7r), with further tables and genealogical diagrams interspersed throughout, some sketched roughly</p>
                        <p>Annotations throughout, many cropped</p>
                        <p>Covers not original: tooled leather binding, with red cartouches aligned centrally</p>
                        <p>Loose folio (f. 174)</p>
                        <p>IOL stamp: 26 May 1910 </p>
                        <p>Microfilm reference: IOL Neg 1267 </p>
                        <p>Flyleaves at end, emblem of 3 feathered tophats with the cipher AFG below</p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per" xml:lang="per">Persian</textLang>
